</p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uvallaen.showPublicProfile?language=EN>vallaen</A> at: 6/25/02 1:35:49 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/urobingoodfellow.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Robin Goodfellow</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 509<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/25/02 1:42:30 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: the peanut gallery says:</span><hr size=1> Syll:<br>
<br>
The fake ID example's a really good one for this, as is Eliezer's drug sale example.  I want to extend both a little further.<br>
<br>
You get ripped off buying a fake ID, get caught at the club/bar, can't get in, get mad, and then decide to sue over it.  Remember, the original poster here has appealed to Verant on this.  No court would enforce your &quot;contract&quot; for a fake ID or for illegal drugs.  If you get scammed, you're just SOL (and not Shadows of Luclin).  In any legitimate contract, the duty of the court would be to restore everyone to the condition they were before the breach was made--but not if the subject of the contract was illegal in the first place.<br>
<br>
Also, Ridale said VI would have trouble enforcing the EULA because people deserve compensation for their work.  This is specious logic.  We're not VI employees--we don't deserve compensation for playing.  The EULA is a contractual agreement, and the terms of that contract are binding unless they are illegal in the state you live in or waive constitutional rights (and this particular term does not).  Even if the work-compensation model were appropriate, and it's not, the EULA would constitute part of the terms-of-employment agreement and still be binding.<br>
<br>
Why doesn't Verant enforce the EULA on this?  Because you can't squeeze blood from a turnip.  The people who are buying and selling accounts probably don't have very much, and Verant would have to prove damages, which would be small potatoes--maybe, at most, $300, although that's a stretch. <p><center><img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~andersonrob/lasgalensig.jpg" border="0"></center>
