<br>
No, but if your account gets banned that is what you 'deserve' - just like if I speed and get a speeding ticket.<br>
<br>
&lt;&lt;  If you are using the EULA as your justification of all things might and holy, then anyone who has shared a password with a friend or loved one is as evil as Zokof and Ogah.  &gt;&gt;<br>
<br>
No, but they did commit the same EULA violation.  However, Ogah took money as part of his.  Ogah basically 'welched' - If you and I have a friendly bet on the Superbowl and I lose and don't pay, you don't have any legal recourse because technically we are not allowed to bet on sports games.  Do you think if a Bookie gets busted by the Cops they go through his books and pay back everyone who gambled?  I see this as the same way.<br>
<br>
&lt;&lt;  I'm still of the beleif that breaking a EULA doesn't give someone a green light to do anything against you other than Verant. It is a contract with them, and what gives Ogah the right to punish for it?  &gt;&gt;<br>
<br>
You are right, no one has the right to 'punish' but that is NOT what happened here.  No one has been punished unless the Account gets banned.  What happened was that one person paid for an illicit service and was conned.  It would be no different than if he gave money to a prostitute and got no sex, or won a bet and wasn't paid.  There is no recourse for these 'rip offs' because they are illicit to begin with.<br>
